<h2>Network Architecture</h2>

<p>The home lab network is segmented into multiple VLANs for security and organization. The main segments include:</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Management Network:</strong> Out-of-band access to server management interfaces</li>
<li><strong>Production Network:</strong> Main network for daily use and trusted devices</li>
<li><strong>Lab Network:</strong> Isolated network for experiments and testing</li>
<li><strong>Vintage Network:</strong> Dedicated segment for older systems with appropriate protocols</li>
<li><strong>IoT Network:</strong> Isolated network for Internet of Things devices</li>
</ul>

<p>The network uses a combination of managed switches, VLANs, and firewall rules to maintain security while allowing necessary communication between segments. A dedicated router running open-source firmware provides advanced routing, VPN access, and network monitoring.</p>

<h2>Services and Applications</h2>

<p>The home lab runs various services for personal use, learning, and experimentation:</p>

<h3>Infrastructure Services</h3>
<ul>
<li>DNS server with local domain resolution and ad blocking</li>
<li>DHCP server with static reservations and network boot support</li>
<li>NTP server for time synchronization across all systems</li>
<li>Certificate authority for internal SSL certificates</li>
<li>Monitoring and alerting with Prometheus and Grafana</li>
</ul>

<h3>Storage and Backup</h3>
<ul>
<li>Network-attached storage with ZFS for data integrity</li>
<li>Automated backup system with versioning and off-site replication</li>
<li>Media server for personal photo and video collection</li>
<li>Document management and archival system</li>
</ul>

<h3>Development and Testing</h3>
<ul>
<li>Git server for personal repositories</li>
<li>Container registry for Docker images</li>
<li>CI/CD pipeline for automated testing and deployment</li>
<li>Virtual machine environment for testing different operating systems</li>
<li>Cross-architecture build environment (x86, ARM, PowerPC)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Current Experiments</h2>

<h3>Cross-Platform Web Testing</h3>

<p>One ongoing experiment involves testing web applications across different browsers and architectures. The vintage systems run period-appropriate browsers (Netscape Navigator 4, Internet Explorer 5, early Mozilla builds) to verify compatibility. This is how I test sites like this one to ensure they work on browsers from 1999 onwards.</p>

<h3>Distributed Computing</h3>

<p>The Raspberry Pi cluster serves as a testbed for distributed computing experiments, including Kubernetes deployments, distributed databases, and consensus algorithms. Working with ARM architecture provides insights into cross-platform development and deployment challenges.</p>

<h3>Network Protocol Studies</h3>

<p>The lab environment allows for experimentation with various network protocols, both modern and legacy. This includes setting up IPv6, testing VPN protocols, experimenting with software-defined networking, and maintaining support for older protocols needed by vintage systems.</p>

<h2>Lessons Learned</h2>

<p>Running a diverse home lab has taught me valuable lessons about compatibility, standards, and the importance of good design. Software that makes assumptions about the underlying platform often fails when moved to a different architecture. Protocols and formats that follow open standards tend to work across diverse systems. Simplicity and clarity in design lead to more maintainable and portable solutions.</p>

<p>These lessons directly inform my approach to software development and web design. The principles that make software work across PowerPC, MIPS, SPARC, and x86 are the same principles that make websites work across different browsers and devices.</p>

